{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958041101/0228.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nUNION JOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, April 11, 1958\nSound Off!\nc\nIONGRESS HAS reached the traditional\nhalfway point and has taken a 10-day\nbreak to return home and sample the po\nlitical and economic temper of the people.\nIt is during this pulse-taking that the\npeople must sound off and channel their\ndiscontent with the ineffective handling of\nthe recession directly to their congressmen\nand senators.\nThere is a tide of dissatisfaction and\nfear running through the nation on the\nlack of concrete action by the White House\nand Congress to put America back to\nwork.\nThere is a real fear that the seven\nmonth-old recession is now feeding on it\nself and that unless drastic steps are taken\nthe country may slip gradually into a state\nof complete economic paraysis.\nPolitically the congressmen and sena\ntors will find that the discontent may pro\nduce significant changes in November.\nEconomically they will discover that\nthe entire nation is a distressed area.\nIn this atmosphere pointing to the rec\nord will not provide the answers. The con\ngressional record is mostly barren of ac\ncomplishments on a real anti-recession\nprogram. The Administration\u2019s record is\ndominated only by a cavalier disregard for\nfacts and an overpowering and unrealistic\ncaution.\nThere has been in both places too much\ntalk, too little effective action.\nThe gentleman\u2019s agreement between\nSpeaker Sam Rayburn and Treasury Sec.\nRobert Anderson for neither side to initi\nate action on a tax cut without informing\nthe other is the dominant characteristic\nof the anti-recession program atmosphere\nin Washington.\n\nTHE ANSWER TO an ineffectual gov\nernment in American political history\nis to improve it or replace it with one that\nwill do the job. And it\u2019s not too early to\nstart.\nPrimary elections around the country\nstart this month.\nThe men and women who will be the\ncandidates for the next Congress, for the\nstate legislatures, for the governors\u2019 man\nsions will be named in these elections.\nIt is the people\u2019s job to get these seek\ners of public office on record on the anti\nrecession program formulated by the\nAFL-CIO\nIt is their job to see that their families\nand friends are registered to vote.\nDuring this Easter recess it is their job\nto visit congressmen and senators and ac\nquaint them with the severity of the reces\nsion and the need for immediate action.\nCongress does not operate in a vacuum;\nwhen the people speak it listens, but the\nvoice must be loud and clear and positive.\nThis is the opportunity to convert a go\nslow Administration and a hesitant Con\ngress into an effective weapon for ending\nthe recession and returning the nation to\nfull production and full employment.\nNot Fooling Anyone\nQINCE HIS RETURN to full-time duty,\nGov. C. William O'Neill has put on a\ndazzling display of fast and nimble foot\nwork, but not fast enough to sidestep a\nfew facts.\nThe Governor, for example, would\nhave us all believe that he had nothing\nto do with the ruling that the unemployed\ncould not receive supplemental unemploy\nment benefits (SUB) in addition to state\ncompensation.\nInstead, the Governor would have us\nblame Administrator James R. Tichenor\nof the Ohio Bureau of Unemployment\nCompensation (BUC) and a certain fellow\nO\u2019Neill referred to as \u201ca former Gover\nnor,\u201d for appointing Tichenor to his job.\nThe \u201cformer Governor\u201d of course, is now\nU. S. Senator Frank J. Lausche.\nThe Akron Beacon Journal comment\ned that O'Neill's claim he was blameless\nwas \u201cinteresting\u201d and that it supposed it\n\u201ccould be\u201d that it was Tichenor who de\ncided SUB contracts are illegal. However,\nit quickly added:\n\u201cBut are we expected to believe that\nTichenor, on his own, decided to fight to\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nOfficial Publication of Organized Labor\nin Northwestern Ohio\nLMOI PRESS\n0\nGrand.\nAward\nW inner\nEntered at Toledo, Ohio, Post Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug. 24, 1912\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nFor Information Phone CH. 1-9128\nWalter Murphy\nBernard Stern\nWilliam Borden\nDerele Collins\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nEdmond A. Pawlicki\nEditor\nAssociate Editor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nJournal Cameramen\nOrville Beemer, Walter Murphy,\nCharles Ballard, Otto Beebe (Local 348),\nErnest Love (Local 1038) Board of Trustees\nDave Huber\nDirector of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCH. 0-4400 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Onion Advertising, N. Y.\n6\nthe bitter end after a Mahoning County\nCommon Pleas Court ruled that he was\nwrong? That it was Tichenor\u2019s idea\u2014and\nonly his\u2014to ask for a stay of execution,\nblocking SUB payments while the appeal\nwas pending? Come, come, Governor!\u201d\nCome, come, Governor, is right! Are\nwe expected to believe that the newspa\npers were wrong in reporting it was the\nGovernor who disregarded the Attorney\nGeneral\u2019s advice not to ask for a stay of\nexecution?\nIt has been the Governor, and the Gov\nernor alone, who has been calling all the\nshots on the SUB question. And he is fool\ning no one when he attempts to place the\nblame elsewhere.\nLet\u2019s not be willy-nilly, Billy.\nA Mistaken Notion\nWE\u2019D LIKE TO ASK management as\nwell as the Senators to take a second\nreading on the notion that weaker unions\nwill mean a stronger free enterprise sys\ntem.\nIt seems to us that this mistaken no\ntion is responsible for the drive for re\nstrictive legislation. It accounts for man\nagement's indecent enthusiasm for the\ntragic revelations of the McClellan Com\nmittee and for the heavy donations to the\nso-called \u201cright-to-work\u201d campaign\nThis belief in bigger-profits-through\nsmaller-unions is being actively promoted\nby a small, well-financed and well-organ\nized group within management, a group\nthat takes the position that an employee\ncannot be a good union member without\nbeing disloyal to his company. They de\nscribe union officers as \u201cpeddlers of hate\u201d\nand labor papers as \u201cbundles of bitter\nness.\u201d They magnify the differences be\ntween union and management representa\ntives and distort a divergent viewpoint\ninto hostility.\nIt seems to us that this management\nviewpoint is at least a generation behind\nthe times. Years ago, some union members\naccepted the class struggle as the only\nway to establish their rights and improve\ntheir lot. In that era, management gave\nplenty of cause for such belief.\nToday, the union members we know\nare convinced that our welfare is bound\nup in the overall welfare of the commun\nity, that we cannot insulate ourselves\nfrom the problems of industry or the na\ntion. In the same way, we believe that the\ncompany and the community cannot pros\nper for long if its wage earners are short\nchanged.\nThe\nsmaller-unions-for-bigger-profits\ncaucus hates to admit that collective bar\ngaining is working remarkably well. They\ndon\u2019t want people to know that the strike\nis the exception to the rule, and that over\nthe past year almost 98 per cent of all\nwage agreements have been reached with\nout any loss of work.\nThey want unions so ineffective that\ncollective bargaining will fail.\nJust what these management strate\ngists expect to find at the end of their\nrainbow is not clear. They cannot serious\nly expect to turn back the clock to an era\nin which management arbitrarily makes\nall the decisions. It\u2019s more logical to as\nsume that they expect eventually to re\nplace collective bargaining with a system\nof wage fixing by Government\u2014a Gov\nernment they, of course, intend to control.\nWeakening unions can only weaken\nthe free enterprise system. Free trade\nunions are as necessary to the system as\nis management.\nThrough The Years I\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\n15 YEARS AGO\nAPRIL 9, 1943: In one of the largest col\nlective bargaining elections in the history of\nthe textile industry, cotton mill workers in 10\nof 11 mills in New Bedford, Mass. chose the\nTextile Workers Union (CIO) as their bar\ngaining agent More than 200 workers of\nthe Surface Combustion Co. were obligated as\nmembers of the Local 12 UAW-CIO, last Sun\nday afternoon by Thomas Burke, Local 12\nvice president, in a ceremony that was cli\nmaxed when members of the organization\nturned in their AFL Machinist Union book\nfor their new UAW-CIO membership card.\n10 YEARS AGO\nAPRIL 9, 1948. Employees of th* Fostoria\nScrew Co. voting in a NLRB election selected\nthe UAW-CIO as their bargaining agent by a\n3 to 1 majority over the International Associa\ntion of Machinists which represented the work\ners for nearly 20 years Endorsement of\nThomas Burke for Congress in the 9th con\ngressional district by the Brotherhood of Loco\nmotive Trainmen was announced last week by\nRichard Lazette, TIUC president The\nNLRB has been breaking records ever since the\nTaft-Hartley law was passed, but unfortunate\nly for organized labor, the record is for 9,468\nundisposed cases at the end of February.\n5 YEARS AGO\nAPRIL\n10,\n1953:\nMel Zimkowski, co\nSecretary of United Labor Committee, an\nnounced that all of the members of Berter\nIndustries have taken out ULC memberships\nMembers of American Floor Surfacing\nUnit of Local 12 are now in the seventh week\nof their strike to get Area Pension, insurance,\nwage boost inaquities and wage adjustments\nto conform with other Local 12 Units\nOver $23,000 has been donated to date to th*\nChildren\u2019s Camp in their drive to get $100,000\nto expand and improve the Camp.\nWelcome Home!\nMyMIIIIT\"TITTTHITHMRI\"INAMHTAHYTHTHILH!IZIMIIMN.AIAII? M\nThink It Over\narbek*2\n./9*1\ncom\u2014\nDRAWH *ORTHE\nAFLCIO News\node\nThe Recession Deepens\nBy PETE ZVARA\nMgNSIAAHIMAAAIMI9MUIIMO***GI*Bmm\nDESPITE ALL the optimistic forecasts that\nhave been hitting the news wires from\nWashington, New York and just about every\nwhere else, it seems that our economic trou\nbles are mounting the slide downward is\ncontinuing and there seems\nto be every indication that\nwe are in for a worse storm\nthan anyone had anticipated.\nUnemployment is steadily\ngetting worse, with the num\nber of our jobless hitting new\npeaks as each week goes by.\nThe steel industry, per\nhaps the most accurate baro\nmeter of our economic health\nthat we know of, has reached\na new low\u2014with operating\ncapacity now being rated at\nPete Zvara\nbelow the 50 per cent mark. And this at a time\nwhen everyone was looking forward to an up\nswing as Spring breaks upon us.\nIn the auto industry the situation is just\nas bad. Whereas at the beginning of this year\nindustry leaders were talking about a produc\ntion run of just under six million cars for this\nyear, now it is no longer news to hear the same\npeople talk about a possible production output\nfor this year just above the four-million mark.\nWhat this means to the industry, and to the\neconomy of our country can well be imagined\nwhen we realize that our output in 1955 was\na little over eight million cars.\nThis enormous drop off in manufacturing,\nof course, is drastically mirrored by what is\nhappening on our railroads Carloading are\nway off and railroad workers with thirty or\nmore years of seniority find themselves job\nless, especially in the operating end of rail\nroading.\nAnd more and more people everywhere\nare asking themselves such questions as these:\nWhat\u2019s happening? Where are we headed for?\nAre we going back to the early thirties?\nAnd surely these are questions that our\ngovernment will soon have to answer or really\nrun the risk of a major economic-political\ncatastrophe.\nWHILE READING about and pondering\nthese serious questions the other day I ran\nacross a news story from Washington telling\nabout a meeting of the International Executive\nBoard of the United Mine Workers of Ameri\nca. And the story tell of a resolution adopted\nby this Board calling upon the federal govern\nment to step into the jobless insurance field\nand provide unemployment compensation pay\nfor all jobless workers of 75\nof their aver\n0\nage pay for an unlimited period.\nIn other words, the UMWA leadership,\nwith the veteran John L. Lewis at their head,\ncalls upon the Eisenhower Administration to\ngo to Congress and request legislation that\nwould take care of this problem once and\nfor all. And they ask for federal action that,\nwould by-pass the several states since it is\nmore than likely that such a program, if left\nup to the individual states, would be killed in\nthe various state legislatures. The proposal, as\nI indicated above, would pay each jobless\nworker 75\n0\nof his average wage and for as\nlong as he is out of work.\nWell, what\u2019s wrong with this proposal?\nTO ANSWER this simple question, we\nmust ask ourselves What is the basic purpose\nof jobless insurance? Simply, it is to provide\nmoney\u2014purchasing power\u2014to workers who\nare jobless through no fault of their own. It\nis a method to help our fellow men when they\nreally need help to keep them off charity\nand relief rolls and thus try to preserve their\nself dignity and in the most humane manner\npossible.\nToday\u2014unlike back in the mid-thirties\nwhen jobless insurance was first proposed and\nthen enacted\u2014no one argues that unemploy\nment compensation will make bums of our\nhonest workers.\nAs a matter of fact today, even the most\nreactionary, the most conservative political,\nbusiness and industrial leaders admit that job\nless pay is one of our \u201cbuilt-in-stabilizers\u201d that\nwill keep our economy from tumbling into\nanother 1929-type depression.\nWhat these gentlemen forget, of course, is\nthat the \u201cbuilt-in-stabilizer\u201d they talk about\u2014\nin this case jobless insurance\u2014cannot quite\nstabilize because of the meagerness of its\nscope.\nWell, if this is so, why are we so hestitant\nabout making adequate provisions to really\nmake it the stabilizer that it should be?\nSOMEHOW THIS discussion brings to mind\nmany possible parallels that in turn, show us\nhow short sighted\u2014and even stupid\u2014we are.\nFor example, if an ocean or airliner needs\nstabilizers, as they do, we build and install\nthem for we know that otherwise their opera\ntion would not be safe.\nIf a doctor determines that a particular\npatient needs a million units of pencilin to\nkill the infection in his body, it would be un\nthinkable for that doctor to prescribe any\nthing less just because it would be cheaper.\nThe patient would die.\nAnd who would be responsible?\nYet that is exactly what the economic\nquacks are doing to our economy and there\nseems to be no one to halt them no one\nto call them to task.\nIT SEEMS TO me that these economic re\ncessions\u2014or even depressions\u2014are nothing but\na disease of our economic life which should be\nattacked the same way as we attack any other\ndisease.\nIn other words, the sooner the leaders of\nour country\u2014together with their big-and-little\nbusinessmen friends\u2014quit deluding themselves\nby talking about built-in-stabilizers that won\u2019t\nand can't stabilize and set about doing things\nright, the sooner we shall solve these economic\nproblems.\nIf unemployment insurance was to cover\nworkers when they are jobless through no\nfault of their own\u2014and I certainly don\u2019t\nmean that we should provide for people who\nrefuse to work when given an opportunity\u2014\nwe should see to it that they are covered. Not\njust partially covered, but covered all the way.\nAll this seems so simple, so elementary.\nSo much so, as a matter of fact, that frequently\nour political and business leaders are forced\nto use economists and college professors to try\nto tell us why\u2014even when they themselves\nknow better\u2014we have to be satisfied with half\nhearted, half-way measures to insure the health\nof our economy.\nNo, there is nothing wrong with the UMWA\nproposal and one day\u2014we hope not before\nlong, not before much more suffering shall\nbe visited upon our people\u2014this proposal will\nbe adopted as it should be and as\nit most certainly will be as soon as reason pre\nvails in this, at.times, almost insane world.\nLetters To The Editor\nPetty Dictatorship\nTO THE EDITOR:\nOur current Governor C. W\nO'Neill has promised on many\noccasions to remove the com\npetitive Civil Service from the\ntaint of the spoils system and\nkeep politics out of it. Here is\nhow he has kept his promise\nin my case:\nI am a war veteran who\nlost a hand. I have ten chil\ndren, three of whom are still\nin school. Some years ago 1\ntook a Civil Service examina\ntion to be a timekeeper in the\nOhio Highway Department\nand passed with a good grade.\nI was appointed permanently\nas timekeeper in my own\ncounty\u2014Seneca. In Septem\nber I was transferred to Wau\nseon, 101 miles from home.\nI took my case to the Civil\nService Commission which\nordered my reinstatement but\nthe dictating powers in the\nHighway Department, for rea\nsons known only to them.\ntried to force me to resign\nand-based their claims on a\nphony charge of insubordina\ntion.\nWhen I refused to resign\nthey gave me a 30-day sus\npension without pay. At the\nend of the 30-day suspension\nI was given a temporary ap\npointment 68 miles from my\nhome and I was refused any\nexpense money which I\nneeded to drive both ways\nMy case was taken to the\nGovernor but he did nothing\nand I am still stationed 68\nmiles from home and it ap*\npears that the ruling power\nis trying to harass me into\nlooking for other work. I\nhave also learned that the\nman who replaced me at\nhome is the husband of the\nRepublican committeewoman\nof Seneca County.\nPetty dictatorship such as*\nthat shown by the present\nAdministration is denying me\nthe right to make an honest\nliving under established Civil\nService rules.\nClaude H. Swartzmiller\nAttica, Ohio\nYour Union\nAnd Mine\ni\nBy RICHARD T. GOSSER\nVice President, UAW\nr\nSEEMS to me that nothing is more insulting to a\nworker or to any member who lives in a free society\nthan for a person or an organization to preach about how\nwonderful democracy is and then to do everything possible\nto destroy it.\nYet this is the very thing the Chamber of Commerce and\nthe Manufacturers Association are doing. They are doing this\nin their campaign to push through this \u201cRight to Work\" law\nwhich they now call a' \u201cFreedom of Choice.\u201d I want to say ser\niously to all workers that the only Freedom they are working\nfor is the freedom to take away your Union which has done so\nmuch to give you a better standard of living: which has given\nyou security on the job and dignity as a human being.\nLet us examine how really democratic'these selfish inter\nests are. They are trying to sell the public on the idea that the\nworker in a shop or factory doesn\u2019t want a union but he has to\njoin or else lose his job.\nI MUST SAY that the selfish employers, the Chamber of\nCommerce and the National Association of Manufacturers really\nbelieved this story when they passed the Taft-Hartley Law in\n1947. In passing this law they wrote into it a provision that be\nfore a Union could get a Union Shop in their contract, the Na\ntional Labor Relations Board had to hold an election, by secret\nballot, and the Union had to win an absolute majority of all eli\ngible workers in a plant.\nThese selfish interest honestly believed they were going to\nget rid of unions with that provision. But let\u2019s see what hap\npened. Between 1947 and 1951 the NLRB, under the law, con- g\nducted 46,119 Union Shop elections. Workers in 44,695 of these\nplants, or in 97.1 per cent of these elections, voted FOR a Union\nShop. Because it was costing so much of the taxpayers\u2019 money\nand taking up so much time, Congress finally had to repeal this\nsection.\nThe greedy employers in the Chamber of Commerce and\nthe Manufacturers Association don\u2019t say anything to the public\nabout these democratic elections. They prefer to keep it secret.\nSince they couldn\u2019t use this provision of the Taft-Hartley law\nto bust Labor Unions, they are now using another section in the\nlaw which allows a state to pass a Right to Bust the Union stat\nute. They also don\u2019t tell the people that this is the only Federal\nLaw which allows a state to make a law which supersedes the\nFederal Government.\nSINCE THESE GROUPS are so democratic, I would like\nto ask them a question. \u201cWhy should a fellow who runs a\ngrocery or drug store or some other shop, or why should a house\nwife have the right to decide whether a person that works in a\nplant can have union security?\u201d\nLet me put that question in another way: Is it democratic\nfor a grocer, or butcher or druggist or housewife to decide what\nkind of union conditions should prevail for workers in a certain\nplant, like Willys, Auto-Lite, Champion or General Motors?\nAll union members, all people should keep one thing in\nmind. The only thing the Chamber of Commerce and the Manu\nfacturers are interested in is to destroy your Union. If you will\nexamine your labor contract you will find that the first article\ngives recognition as a bargaining agent to the Union.\nThe employers don\u2019t want to have to bargain with the work\ners collectively. So all they have to do to deal with you one by\none is to get rid of the Union. That is the reason for their trying\nto pass a \u201cRight to Work\u201d or \u201cFreedom of Choice\u201d law. If you\nrealize this fact and take steps to protect yourself and your\nfamily by registering and voting and acquainting your friends\nand neighbors and relatives, you will also be protecting your\njob security and your standard of living.\nBulletin Board\nMeetings scheduled for week of April 12 thru April 18\nSaturday, April 12\nKIDS PARTY 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nBINGHAM ELECTION 12:00 P.M. Parlor A\nBALLARDS CLASSIC\nBOWLING LEAGUE 3:00 P.M. Parlor B\nINDUSTRIAL HEAT 7:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSPICER SKILLED TRADES 9:30 A.M. Parlor C\nTOLEDO STAMPING 2:00 P.M. Parlor C\nW. O. SKILLED TRADES 10:00 A.M. Parlor H\nPRESSED STEEL 2:00 P.M. Parlor H\nSunday, April 13\nSPICER STEWARDS 8:00 A.M. Parlor A\nSPICER MEMBERS 10:00 A.M. \u2014Pallor A\nSKILLED TRADES 1:00 P.M. Parlor A\nPEERLESS PLASTICS 2:00 .M. Parlor B\nMATHER 9:00 A.M. Parlor H\nPETERS STAMPING 2:00 P.M. Parlor H\nMonday, April 14\nBARRETT 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nBARRETT 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nBARRETT STEWARDS 9:00 A.M. Parlor B\nBARRETT STEWARDS 7:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSAVE ELECTRIC 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nTuesday, April 15\nF. E. P. C. 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nCOUSINO METAL PROD. 4:00 P.M. Parlor B\nASSOC. PRODUCTS 7:30 P.M. Parlor B\nSPICER OFFICE 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nPEERLESS PLASTICS 1:00 P.M. Parlor H\nPEERLESS PLASTICS 8:00 P.M. Parlor H\nWednesday, April 16\nGUILD BOWLING LEAGUE 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nAYLING 7:30 P.M. Parlor B\nAMERICAN MOTORS 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nIND. FINISHERS 8:00 P.M. Parlor H\nThursday, April 17\nPENSION CLUB\nCARD PARTY 12:30 P.M. Parlor A\nPIPE THREADING 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nCAMERA CLUB 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nVICTOR SCREW 8:00 P.M. Board Room\nPORCELAIN 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nCAMP COUNSELLORS 7:00 P.M. Parlor H\nODLAND, STD. TOOL, WATSON,\nWELEVER, McCOLL,\nTOTH 8:00 P.M. 4th Floor Raps. Room\nFriday, April 18\nW. O. STEWARDS 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nAMVETS 7:30 P.M. Rest Room\nBARON STEEL 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nSAM EARLEY 8:00 P.M. Parlor H","height":"26840","width":"19532"}}
